  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Technical support for AWD response in Addis Ababa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Acute Watery Diarrhoea (AWD) outbreak in Addis Abba continues to evolve. As of 26 June 2016, a total of 1,092 cases and one death (CFR 0.09%, AR 0.03%) had been reported from all ten (10) sub cities and all 120 woredas / districts since the outbreak was confirmed on 7 June 2016 by laboratory culture. The outbreak has now spread to Oromia woredas adjacent to Addis Ababa city. AWD outbreaks have been going on in other parts of the country since November 2015. By 26 June 2016, a total of 3,323 AWD cases and 29 deaths (CFR 0.87%, AR 0.05%) had been reported from 115 woredas/districts in 19 zones of Oromia, Somali, SNNP regions and 10 sub cities of Addis Ababa. During the week ending 26 June, new outbreaks were reported in two woredas of SNNP region, which had not reported AWD for about 12 weeks. The laboratory confirmed case is the same strain as that reported in Moyale it is therefore thought to have spread from there. Responses to all these outbreaks are being coordinated by national command post led by the state minister. 
The potential of this outbreak to further spread from Addis Ababa to other regions is very high hence the urgent need to control this outbreak, especially given the imminent onset of the rainy season. Addis Ababa city is noted for high convergence of people and diverging movement of people both within and outside the country, which is a regional hub, hence there is the potential risk of further spread.
In addition there are already existing disease outbreaks including measles, typhoid and chikungunya in other parts of the country, and severe acute malnutrition.</narrative>
  </description>
